[2
Date: 21 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Pravda (English) [edited
<http://english.pravda.ru/world/2001/07/21/10720.html>

In Lorraine, France another case of mad cow disease (BSE, Bovine
Spongiform Encephalopathy) has been registered. So far 346 cases of
this cattle disease have been reported. The diseased animal was
discovered at a livestock farm in the Moselle department. The farm is
adjacent to other farms.
A 10km quarantine zone was established around each farm, in accordance
with France's sanitary norms. [Access to the farms is guarded by
reinforced police teams. Diseased animals are to be destroyed.
­­
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
******
[3
Date: 25 Jul 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ANIMALNET: [edited

The French government has lowered the age at which cattle must be
tested for bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE) from 30 months to 24
months, according to France's Agriculture Ministry.
Additionally, beginning tomorrow, all cows aged 24 months and older
will be tested for BSE before being slaughtered, the ministry added.
According to the ministry, between 1 Jan and 15 Jul 2001, more than
one million cows were tested for BSE. Of those tested, 31 infected
cows were detected.
­­
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
